		●參考書資料暨網路資源 Reference Books and Online ResourcesPart I.&	Davis, Michael C. 1995. Human Rights and Chinese Values: Legal, Philosophical, and Political Perspectives. Hong Kong, New York: Oxford University Press.&	Glendon, Mary Ann. 2001. A World Made New: Eleanor Roosevelt and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. New York: Random House.&	Rawls, John. 1993. Political Liberalism. New York: Columbia University Press.&	Sen, A. 1997. “Human rights and Asian Values”. The New Republic, 217, 33-40. Retrieved from http://search.proquest.com/docview/212785609?accountid=13952&	Spence, Jonathan. 1982. The Gate of Heavenly Peace: The Chinese and Their Revolution: 1895-1980. Penguin Books.&	Taylor, Charles. 1999. “Conditions of an Unforced Consensus on Human Rights.” In The East Asian Challenge for Human Rights, edited by Joanne R. Bauer and Daniel A. Bell, 124-144. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.&	Teng, Ssu Yu and John Fairbank. 1979. China’s Response to the West: A Documentary Survey, 1839-1923. Harvard University Press.&	Zhou, Cezong. 1960. The May Fourth Movement: Intellectual Revolution in Modern China. Cambridge: Harvard University Press.Part II.&	Fairbank, John King. 1968. The Chinese World Order: Traditional China's Foreign Relations. Cambridge: Harvard University Press.&	Gaddis, John Lewis. 2011. George F. Kennan: An American Life. New York: Penguin.&	Kennedy, Paul. 1987. The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers: Economic Change and Military Conflict from 1500 to 2000. Random House.&	Kissinger, Henry. 2012. On China, reprint ed. New York: Penguin.&	Mearsheimer, John J. 2001. The Tragedy of Great Power Politics. New York: Norton.&	Vogel, Ezra. 2013. Deng Xiaoping and the Transformation of China. Belknap Press; Reprint edition.Part III.&	Chi, Su. 2008. Taiwan's Relations with Mainland China: A Tail Wagging Two Dogs. Routledge.&	Chu, Yun-han. 1992. Crafting Democracy in Taiwan. Taipei: Institute for National Policy Research.&	Bush, Richard C. 2013. Uncharted Strai