三、教學目標 Objectives


本課程分為六個部份。第一個部份探討中國從19世紀以來與西方文化的互動，以及對一種非強制性人權共識的追求。廣泛來說，近百年來，中國政府與一些知識分子基於文化優越感或民族主義，而對於普世人權標準抱持著敵意。只有一小群的知識份子獻身於普世人權標準，挺身而出，挑戰政府。近年來，一群接受歐美教育而在台灣工作的知識分子倡導人權標準與中國傳統思想－尤其是儒家文化－可以相互契合。但我認為，倡導中西文化的對話可以有不同的論述與途徑。第二部份分析當代中國國強必霸的爭論，一方面現實主義國際理論學者傾於中國必將稱霸，與美國發生衝突，而中國的領導階層卻強調中國必不稱霸。在當前東海與南海爭端的背景之下，我們的問題是：國際組織與國際秩序的建立，尤其是聯合國的運作，是否為國際關係帶來不一樣的局面？能否和平解決爭端，進而預防軍事衝突以及戰爭？第三部份處理中國與台灣的關係，也就是統和獨的爭論，並涉及到台灣內部藍營與綠營的僵持不下。我們試探尋找一個突破，強調基於這30年來台灣與國際人權標準的接軌，以及新移民與移工在台灣社會影響日增，假以時日，必定在價值觀念以及人口結構上發生基本的改變，也為藍營、綠營之爭，以及中國與台灣的僵局，帶來新的可能性。第四部份討論中國與西藏的關係。我們將關註集中於北京這幾十年來對西藏的統治，另一方面探討自從達賴𡃤嘛流亡印度之後，流亡政府的政策。我們要問的問題是，達賴𡃤嘛的中間路線是否可行？又國際法對解決中國與西藏的關係能不能發揮怎麼樣的作用？第五部份探討中國的革命，尤其是毛澤東思想帶來的影響。我們的問題是，毛澤東憑藉什麼、又在什麼情況之下取得在思想上、政策上絕對的主導權？而又怎麼樣一步一步帶來烏托邦的幻滅？馬克思思想在中國是不是必然走向烏托邦？第六部份探討近30年來台灣與國際人權規範的接軌。為什麼台灣願意這樣作？面對什麼樣的問題？又達到什麼樣的成效？這個課程並非傳統的歷史研究，而是跨領域的探討。我們不要求選課的同學對中國研究有多少的背景，但同學們應該按步就班閱讀指定教材，以及參與課堂討論。期中考試為申論題，期末考可選擇參加考試或繳交期末報告。 


As indicated in the course title, the focus of this study is on the entanglements, cultural, political and territorial of China with the West and the world community in the past hundred years.It will be divided into six parts. The first part will take up the cultural encounter between China and the West, a quest for modernity and in our time, a search for an unforced consensus on human rights. Broadly speaking, through the hundred years, Chinese governments and part of the intellectual elite tended to be hostile toward universal human rights standards, motivated either by a sense of cultural superiority or nationalism. Only a tiny group of intellectuals was committed to universal human rights standards, challenging their government. Of late quite a few intellectuals educated in Europe and the United States and working in Taiwan were inclined to argue for the compatibility of traditional Chinese thought, especially that of Confucianism, with universal human rights standards. There is, however, more to this narrative and different approaches to the reconciliation of China and the West will be examined.The second part will deal with the conflicts and wars that China was engaged in since the Opium War in the 1840s, with special attention paid to the Korean War, the wars in Vietnam and the contemporary crisis in the East Sea and South Sea. The question asked is whether China will opt for hegemony in Asia or the rise of international organizations and international law, such as the League of Nations and the United Nations, the IMF (International Monetary Fund) and the World Bank etc. and China’s participation in them made a difference? Did they make peaceful resolution of conflicts possible, and thus preventing military clash and war?The third part will be devoted to ideological historical and territorial disputes. Between China and Taiwan, it will examine the desire of the People’s Republic of China to unify Taiwan, and on the opposite side, the movement for political independence. Here, cultural, political as well as territorial disputes converged. What will be the future for Taiwan will be the focus of the study.The fourth part will tackle the relations between China and Tibet, how Beijing ruled Tibet and whether international law can help settle the dispute.The fifth part will turn to the rise of Maoism and his utopian project. The question is if there a tendency for Marxism in China to become utopian, ending in great disasters and disillusion?The six part will describe and analyze the experience of Taiwan in joining the international human rights regime and what impact it has domestically and internationally. 


四、課程內容 Course Description


●整體敘述 Overall DescriptionIt is recognized that this course is not a conventional historical study, but an in-depth multidisciplinary research into the complex relations among China, Taiwan and the West since the collapse of the Ching Dynasty in China. This course is open to students from all different disciples. They are encouraged to do the required readings and participate in discussion. A mid-term examination is mandated, and for the final, either an examination or a term paper will be required.

